<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;">ANDREA MITCHELL: In Havana, dramatic change after=
 more than a half-century. Tomorrow the Cold War will be over. A huge openi=
ng for U.S. and Cuban travel and trade. In Havana, Nelson Fernandez says th=
ese measures help the country's economy. Orlando, a restaurant cook, says w=
e think more Americans will come. There is still an embargo on general tour=
ists, but a lot more Americans can go more easily. Educational groups, cult=
ural groups, journalists, medical and religious organizations, family visit=
s.</p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;">ALEX RIVAS: I got two daughters in Cuba. I have t=
o go.</p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;">MITCHELL: At the Miami airport Alex Rivas has a n=
ew baby who has never seen its grandmother.</p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;"><img class=3D"image-blog_body-50" style=3D"max-wi=
dth: 100//newsbusters.org/s3/files/styles/blog_body-50/s3/images/2015-01-15-NBC-NN-=
Cuba3.JPG?itok=3DEaCoCuER" alt=3D"" width=3D"280">VIVAS: I have a 4-month k=
id and don't know his grandma right now.</p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;">MITCHELL: And soon he can fly on a regularly sche=
duled commercial flight, not just the current commercial limited charters. =
He can use the internet when he gets there as internet companies jump in. U=
se a credit card, not just cash. Until now, no U.S. credit was allowed in C=
uba. Plus, credit opens the door for ten times the current grain sales from=
 Iowa farmers like Bob Bowman.</p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;">NATIONAL CORN GROWERS ASSOCIATION&rsquo;S BOB BOW=
MAN: When we travel to Cuba, the Cuban government officials were almost beg=
ging us to open up trade with them.</p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;">CNBC CHIEF INTERNATIONAL CORRESPONDENT MICHELLE C=
ARUSO-CABERRA We know there is a huge appetite for building equipment, thin=
gs like paint, things to repair your home because so many of the homes ther=
e are in disrepair.</p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;">MITCHELL: And cigars, so prized John Kennedy got =
a stash of more than 1,000 for himself before imposing the embargo. America=
ns will still only be able to bring back $100 worth. That is about three co=
hibas, Cuba's best.</p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;"><img class=3D"image-blog_body-50" style=3D"max-wi=
dth: 100//newsbusters7.s3.amazonaws.com/styles/blog_body-50/s3/images/2015-01-15-NB=
C-NN-Cuba2.JPG?itok=3D9YPG74ih" alt=3D"" width=3D"280">(....)</p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;">MITCHELL: But there were plenty of Americans in H=
avana today all there from special tour groups and by tomorrow they can spe=
nd more money and use credit cards. Critics say the President is going too =
far violating the embargo and many ask whether Cuba is really ready for the=
 American economic invasion, especially internet access for all Cubans.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;">The transcript of the brief from ABC&rsquo;s <i>W=
orld News Tonight with David Muir </i>on January 15 can be found below.</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;">ABC&rsquo;s <i>World News Tonight With David Mui<=
/i>r<br> January 15, 2015<br> 6:41 p.m. Eastern</p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;"><img class=3D"image-blog_body-50" style=3D"max-wi=
dth: 100//newsbusters.org/s3/files/styles/blog_body-50/s3/images/2015-01-15-ABC-WNT=
-Cuba.JPG?itok=3D5D49tq4T" alt=3D"" width=3D"280">[ON-SCREEN HEADLINE CAPTI=
ON: New Rules]</p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 14px; font-weight: normal; line-height: 1.6; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 10px;">DAVID MUIR: Beginning tomorrow, travel and trade =
with Cuba will be a little easier, just weeks after lifting the embargo in =
place since the Cold War. New moves from the White House. Americans will be=
 allowed to visit Cuba without getting special permits. They will be able t=
o use credit cards while there and bring back small amounts of rum and ciga=
rs. Businesses, also now allowed to sell Cuban telephones, computers, and i=
nternet technology.</p>
</blockquote>
